<br>
4. When the shout goes out for &quot;Cleric camp&quot; don't yell &quot;Which one?&quot;, sit your ass down and camp! I've seen it happen 3 times already and all 3 times we ended up with no clerics camped due to only needing a few more seconds for the idiot cleric to camp. Those few seconds he took to yell &quot;Which one?&quot; would have given us a camped cleric. Also don't sit down under the mob and expect to camp. Back up at least a little ways to give you a better chance of camping, not too far mind you, just give yourself a little space. I know mobs summon you and they move around a lot but all casters should try something that I do. As long as the camp is broken and the way is clear then try to stay about 3/4 of your casting range out. Once you've been there a while (few times) you'll know where you can safely move around your camp without drawing in a mob. By staying in this range you can still nuke or heal without having to move yourself unless the mob has a major mental breakdown and moves half way across the planes. For a pure caster you may have to be less than 3/4 since I know a few of your spells have a wide range.<br>
<br>
5. Tanks.... geez guys, calm down!!!<br>
I've seen it over and over: &quot;INCOMING!!!!!&quot;. All tanks who are sitting stand up and move along with all the tanks who were standing towards the direction that we are pulling from. STOP IT!!!! First off you get out of range from your casters and we end up having to move. That takes our time out of medding for that last drop of mana to save your hide and also delays any heals that you need since the cleric is having to come your way. See item 4 for more reasons not to move. It's a range thang, remember that. Anyway we made it through that battle. Now, everybody back to the camp!!! Crap!! Why do I have to keep moving?? Let the pullers bring the mob to the camp, not take the camp to the mobs. Guess what?!?! That's why they are called pullers.<br>
<br>
6. Leaders<br>
Give more feedback on mana within the group. If somebody is below 50 then let the pullers know you need a bit more time or at least ask the person if they need more time. This doesn't count for unexpected mobs but rather just the mobs you know are being pulled. Clerics in this case are a strange lot. We buff till we are blue in the face there so at hardly any time will we be FM. If you have a good cleric then he'll damned sure tell you if he needs more time since he has an idea on how much healing he has had to do in the past within your group. He'll also be the seesaw in your works. One minute he's FM and the next he's OOM. How the hell you ask when nobody has been hit enough to need a heal? It's called buffs. I'll explain more about this in item 7. Back on topic. Leaders give more feedback on who is AFK within your group. If the camp is moving then DO NOT let the camp move till all of your members are back from AFK. It's happened every time I've been to the planes, somebody gets left in the old camp because they were AFK. Almost every time this has happened we'd end up with a few extra mobs to take care of since somebody got lost and is roaming around. &quot;WOW I made it.&quot; Oh yeah, I brought a few friends for us to kill. That just don't cut it most of the time.<br>
<br>
7. Clerics.<br>
Some of you clerics are gonna hate me for this one but YOU are giving some of us clerics a bad rap. We are not tanks or casters, we are healer and buffers and on occasion stunners. If you are not doing one of the three things I've mentioned as your job then you better be on your ass medding. Over and over I see &quot;Cleric OOM&quot; and I've sat there and watched the cleric nuke away all of his mana. Sure, throw in a few nukes once in a while to at least make us feel better but DO NOT blow all of your mana on nukes. If you are buffing, healing, and stunning correctly, you don't have a lot of extra mana to waste on nukes.<br>
<br>
